Summary:
The Dyalog Cookbook sets out how to build in Dyalog an application that can be shared or sold commercially.

This workshop reviews the opening chapters, identifying issues and exploring solutions. The focus will be on understanding the problems to be solved in packaging an application for distribution, and the solutions on offer.

Topics include:

  • How to structure the workspace
  • Exporting a stand-alone executable
  • Logging events
  • Handling errors
  • Writing, using, and maintaining tests
  • Providing online help
  • Writing an installer
  • Managing source code

This workshop continues in session SP1, which focuses on getting hands on experience with the tools and scripts of the book. If you are already familiar with the topics of the book and want only to acquaint yourself with its tools, then workshop SP1 can be attended without attending workshop SA1.
Title: SA1: CookBook Part I (Stephen Taylor & Kai Jaeger)

Summary: In the immortal words of Pete Donnelly, "Programming with threads requires care". If all goes well, you will leave this workshop with a good idea of how to use threads safely and efficiently to make your application more responsive and increase performance. The workshop will cover the use of tokens for thread synchronisation and show how threading can be used to take full advantage of futures and isolates.
Title: SA2: Threading and Synchronisation (Morten Kromberg & Adam Brudzewsky)
SA3: Web Application Development I (Michael Baas & Brian Becker)
SA4: Compiler & Performance Features (Jay Foad & Roger Hui)
SP1: CookBook Part II (Stephen Taylor & Kai Jaeger)
SP2: Artificial Neural Networks in APL (Romilly Cocking & Aaron Hsu)
SP3: Taming Statistics with TamStat (Steve Mansour)
SP4: A Tour (de Force) of APL in 16 Expressions (Roger Hui)
TP1: V15 in Depth (Dan Baronet & Adam Brudzewsky)
TP2: Compiling ANN & other APL Code (Aaron Hsu & Romilly Cocking)
TP3: Web Application Development II (Michael Baas & Brian Becker)
TP4: Data Visualisation (Gitte Christensen, Nicolas Delcross, John Daintree & Brian Becker)

Summary: Richard and Michael will review tools for working with external data in a variety for formats: Comma Separated Values, JSON, XML will be covered, as well as alternatives to COM Automation for working with Excel data files- and serialisation and compression of APL arrays.
Title: SA1: Text-Based Data Sources (R. Smith & M. Baas)

Summary: In this workshop you will learn about tools for starting and managing multiple processes. Keywords: Conga, APLProcess, RPCServer, Futures and Isolates, Windows Services and UNIX daemons.
Title: SA2: Services and Multi-Process Applications (B. Christensen & M. Kromberg)

Summary: The gurus are back with another round of tips and tricks aimed at making your code run faster – with special focus on features recently added to Dyalog APL.
Title: SA3: Performance Tuning (R. Hui, M. Lochbaum & J. Foad)

Summary: Bring your own data to a half-day introduction to SharpPlot and SharpLeaf, the graphics and publication tools which are included with Dyalog APL on all platforms.
Title: SA4: SharpPlot and SharpLeaf (N. Delcros)

Summary: In Depth: A review of the most important features of Dyalog APL version 16.0, by the people who designed and implemented many of them.
Title: SP1: Version 16.0 In Depth (J. Scholes, R. Smith & R. Hui)

Summary: Compared to the 2016 edition, the 2017 co-dfns compiler supports more language features, and is significantly easier to install and use from Dyalog APL. Bring your own code and learn how to compile it (to run on your GPU if you have one – or serially if not).
Title: SP3: Co-dfns Hands On (A. Hsu)

Summary: This workshop will present the details of the implementation of two production web applications written in Dyalog APL and MiServer: TryAPL and the new Event Registration System used for Dyalog’17.
Title: TP1: Anatomy of Two Web Applications (B. Becker & M. Baas)

Summary: Bring your own small application and at the end of this workshop you should have it up and running under Amazon Web Services and/or Microsoft Azure… Includes an introduction to running under Linux for Windows bigots, RIDE, and a few words about service authentication using Certificates.
Title: TP2: Cloud Deployment (A. Shiers & M. Kromberg)

Summary: In continuation of the Sunday Performance workshop, join us for a light-hearted but deadly serious Code Golf Hackathon with problems designed to help you learn to take advantage of recent language features.
Title: TP3: Code Golf Hackathon (A. Brudzewsky, M. Lochbaum, R. Hui & J. Foad)

Summary: An informal discussion about how mobile development with Dyalog could be done. We'll start with last year's "Airfix" model, and talk about what's good, what's bad, and where we want to be".
Title: TP4: Mobile Development Discussion (J.Daintree)
